text:
Yeah, that really annoyed me, because all of the whining brats were wrong. The game auto-saves. The map is useless for the tunnels. In the beginning of the game none of the skills you can evolve are good for attack/defence/speed etc - so since she never uses the sonar as it's intended it was completely pointless for her to upgrade it anyways (which was the only skill she could upgrade). The only way to become stronger is by eating / leveling up and finding the collectibles. If she had had more motivation and continued, as her goal was to eat more humans she would have attracted the hunters and if she had managed to kill the first "hunter boss" (which is just jumping on the boat and eating him) she would have gotten the bio-electric jaws. Eating humans is one of the easiest ways to stack up nutrients. So she unknowingly already was on the right track and would have gotten stronger just fine.

The only thing she'd need to practice is the fighting which is actually really scripted for all big animals. Dodge > attack - or attack just before they charge you. Or like I did for most of the time button-mash the chomp button and just chew on them until they die.

Funnily enough the way she acted in the game was rather natural for a shark. xD

Another bonus fact: orcas are actually from the family of dolphins. Funny how one of the friendliest animals, bottlenose dolphins, are closely related to one of the strongest and one of the most aggressive animal of our present time, the orcas.

text: Tricky thing about exiting that pipe in the tunnels, is this game has a deceptive aspect, where if you try to jump over an obstacle while being right next to it, you will have absolutely no forward momentum and won't clear it. It looks really weird because the animation makes it look like you have some forward momentum regardless, so it almost looks like you're hitting an invisible wall. The trick is to jump early while swimming fast so that you can jump at like an arcing angle to clear those obstacles. Either that, or you backtrack the entire way back through the tunnels lol.

text:
I don't really understand this mentality when it comes to a lot of streamers. Isn't a stream meant to be interaction between a streamer and their audience? And if the streamer is clearly struggling or missing key components to the game wouldn't it be advantageous to give them tips since we're there?

Let me give a hypothetical example: when I first played Bloodborne, I missed the weapons you get in the beginning of the game, and played 2 hours into the game at a disadvantage that was not intended to be there.  If I had been streaming that game, it would be unreasonable to expect a potential audience to be hush hush about what I missed. Relating that here, don't you think she would enjoy the game more if we let her know about the fast travel earlier in the stream?

It's another thing if chat was spoiling secrets or trying to get her to play with very specific play styles. And pardon me if I missed anything but most of what I saw were people telling her to save the game or read the information in the menus.
author: @intestinalclouds-kfpobitua5342

text:
¬†@intestinalclouds-kfpobitua5342¬† Games are something that you play. How you play and what you learn is different for each person. The very point of games is that people learn and play at their own pace. 

The streamers who play are adults. They are more than capable of asking for help once they feel like they aren't doing good. Which is exactly what she did. Spamming the comments telling her what to do isn't helpful. There is no "interaction" between streamers and chat there. It's "policing". Telling you how to play the game without letting you figure it out yourself. For example, spamming the comments with "save" when "autosave" was already a function. Made it clear that most people wanted to feel like they are contributing for the sake of it and not because they actually want to be helpful.
